This Week's Reads

A Look at the United States

The United States is a big country in North America. Its capital city is Washington D.C., a special place where the White House is. Around 340 million people live in the U.S., making it one of the most populated countries. (This means a huge number of people call the U.S. home.) People from all over the world live there, making it very diverse. The money used is the U.S. Dollar. The government has three main parts: one makes laws, one carries them out, and one checks if they are fair. (These three parts are called branches: Legislative makes laws, Executive carries them out, and Judicial checks fairness. They work together so no single part gets too much power.) This helps keep things balanced. The U.S. is also a strong country that works with other nations to help keep peace and trade around the world.

Difficult Vocabulary Words
  • Republic (리퍼블릭 / 공화국): A type of government where citizens choose representatives to make laws for them. It is not led by a king or queen.
  • Legislative (레지슬레이티브 / 입법의): Having the power to make laws. In the U.S., Congress is the legislative branch.
  • Executive (이그제큐티브 / 행정의): Having the power to carry out and manage laws. In the U.S., the President leads the executive branch.
  • Judicial (주디셜 / 사법의): Having the power to interpret laws and decide if they are fair. In the U.S., the Supreme Court is part of the judicial branch.
  • Constitutional (컨스티튜셔널 / 헌법의): Related to a country's main set of laws (the constitution) that defines how the government works and protects people's rights.

Go Hiking!

Hiking is a fun sport. You walk on trails in nature. It helps your body get strong. (This means hiking helps your muscles and heart.) It also helps you feel calm and happy. When you hike, wear good shoes. These shoes keep your feet safe. (This means special shoes protect your feet.) Bring water to drink. Take snacks like fruit. Always tell a grown-up where you go. Stay on the path. This keeps you safe. Hiking is a great way to see pretty views!

Difficult Vocabulary Words
  • Recreational (레크리에이션의): Relating to or denoting activity done for enjoyment when one is not working.
  • Ascend (오르다, 올라가다): To go up or climb.
  • Descend (내려오다, 내려가다): To go or come down.
  • Crampons (아이젠): Metal frames with spikes that attach to boots for walking on ice or snow.
  • Gaiters (스패츠): A covering of cloth or leather that extends from the instep to the ankle or knee, worn over shoes and trousers for protection.

Our Amazing Planets

Planets are huge, round space objects that go around a star. The word "planet" means "wanderer." Our solar system has eight planets. They are Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. Some are rocky, like Earth and Mars. We call these terrestrial planets. (This means they have a solid, rocky surface.) Other planets are giant and mostly made of gas, like Jupiter and Saturn. We call these gas giants. Dwarf planets are smaller, round objects that also orbit the Sun, but they haven't cleared their path. Pluto is one! Planets outside our solar system are called exoplanets. (These are planets orbiting stars other than our Sun.) Planets do not make their own light; they reflect their star's light.

Difficult Vocabulary Words
  • Terrestrial (지구형 행성/육상의): Relating to Earth or a planet similar to Earth, especially having a solid, rocky surface.
  • Exoplanet (외계 행성): A planet outside our solar system, orbiting another star.
  • Eccentric (이심률이 큰/별난): (Describing an orbit) Not perfectly circular; somewhat oval or egg-shaped.
  • Retrograde (역행성의/역행하는): Moving backward or in the opposite direction to most other objects in a system.
  • Celestial (천체의/하늘의): Relating to the sky or outer space, or things in it, like stars and planets.

Test Your Knowledge!

Hey there, future knowledge masters! Get ready to test your brains with our awesome General Knowledge Quiz! See how many you can get right!

1. Which planet in our solar system is famous for its giant red spot and is the largest of them all?

A) Mars
B) Saturn
C) Jupiter
D) Earth
Answer: C) Jupiter. Jupiter is so big, all the other planets could fit inside it!

2. What is the capital city of the United States of America?

A) New York City
B) Los Angeles
C) Washington, D.C.
D) Chicago
Answer: C) Washington, D.C. It's where the President lives and the White House is located!

3. When you go hiking, what is the most important type of gear to protect your feet and provide good grip on uneven trails?

A) Sandals
B) Running shoes
C) Hiking boots
D) Flip-flops
Answer: C) Hiking boots. They're designed to support your ankles and give you traction on rough paths!

4. Which planet in our solar system is known as the "Red Planet" because of its reddish appearance?

A) Venus
B) Mercury
C) Mars
D) Uranus
Answer: C) Mars. The red comes from iron minerals in its soil that rust!

5. What famous landmark in New York City was a gift from France and stands as a global symbol of freedom and democracy?

A) The Empire State Building
B) The Statue of Liberty
C) Times Square
D) The Brooklyn Bridge
Answer: B) The Statue of Liberty. Lady Liberty welcomes millions of visitors every year!
